Notes:
Simul led the whole thing in 4 blocks. Couldn’t wipe a grin off my face the whole time. Climbing was somewhat scrambly, but it didn’t matter when you turned around to look at the view. And tallest point in the lower 48!! Great day

Timing notes: hiking at 3:25am, dropped packs at Iceberg at 6:40a (3hr15), climbing from 7:30a-10:30a. We were cruising until the third simul blocked dragged a bit and I had to do some looking for the best route. And then there was a false summit so I just pulled Adam up on the old hand belay and did one more simul block. Took our time going down, nice break at our packs and then at the outlet stream of UBS, and hit the car at 3pm.

Notes:
An “ordeal” with Miller. Challenging approach. We didn’t have traction for the snow which was interesting. In the end approach just took us too much time, as well there was a party of 3 on the route when we got there. Miller led through the finger crack as P1, then all the way to the base of the splitter as P2 (top of P4). I followed the fingers clean which was cool, but French freed the crap out of the chimney. But we followed our discussed turn around time and got back to the car safely just before dark, so definitely counts as a successful alpine day. 
Timing: Started hiking at 8:30am, hit Burgundy Col at 12:00pm (3.5hrs), started climbing at 1:30pm, started rapping at 4:30pm, snow saddle at 6:00pm, back to cars right at 9pm. 12.5hrs C2C.
Location: Washington > Northwest Region > Hwy 20 and North Cascades National Park > North Cascades > Washington Pass > Silver Star and Wine Spires > Chianti Spire

1hr17 car to base, 3hr on route. 6.5hrs C2C
